INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9b0cb2cf-d321-4592-92c4-aff36041f1e7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vue computed() — When Memoization Helps vs Hurts$escape$,
  $escape$Vue's `computed()` memoizes derived state automatically — it caches the result and only recomputes when reactive dependencies change. This is Vue's primary memoization primitive, not a manual optimization like React's `useMemo`. The distinction matters: wrapping a simple property access in `computed()` adds overhead with zero benefit. It shines when the derivation is expensive — filtering a large array, transforming a dataset, or building a lookup map from reactive source data.

Vue has no `useCallback` equivalent because methods defined in `<script setup>` are stable references by default — they don't recreate on render. If you're passing a method as a prop to a child using `defineProps`, the reference stays stable without any wrapping.

Over-memoizing hurts: every `computed()` registers a watcher and allocates a cache slot. For trivial derivations (`fullName = firstName + ' ' + lastName`), the watcher overhead exceeds savings. Reserve `computed()` for derivations that are either expensive to calculate or shared across multiple template expressions — reading the same derived value twice in a template already benefits from a single `computed()` cache.$escape$,
  $escape$import { ref, computed } from 'vue'

const products = ref<Product[]>([])
const query = ref('')

// Good: expensive filter memoized — only reruns when products or query changes
const filteredProducts = computed(() =>
  products.value.filter(p =>
    p.name.toLowerCase().includes(query.value.toLowerCase())
  )
)

// Bad: trivial derivation — computed() overhead outweighs any benefit
// const label = computed(() => `${firstName.value} ${lastName.value}`)
// Just use a method or inline template expression instead$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
