INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7d9a6838-0d7f-44c8-bde2-008b3fc36963',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vue Testing Library — Test What Users See, Not What Vue Knows$escape$,
  $escape$Vue Test Utils makes it tempting to assert on internal state: `wrapper.vm.isLoading`, `wrapper.vm.handleSubmit()`, or `wrapper.vm.$emit`. These tests break on safe refactors—rename a ref, extract a composable, and your suite turns red despite zero user-visible change.

@testing-library/vue flips the model. Query the DOM the way a user navigates it: `getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i })`, `getByLabelText('Email')`, `findByText('Success')`. Fire events with `userEvent.click()` rather than calling component methods directly.

This matters most with composables. If `useAuth` internally swaps from a `ref` to a `reactive` object, a behaviour-first test doesn't care—it just checks whether the login button appears after a successful call. Implementation tests would shatter.

The rule: if your test imports the component's internal symbols or reads `wrapper.vm.*`, it's testing implementation. If it only reads the rendered output and fires DOM events, it's testing behaviour. Only the latter survives real-world iteration.$escape$,
  $escape$import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/vue'
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event'
import LoginForm from './LoginForm.vue'

test('shows welcome message after successful login', async () => {
  render(LoginForm)

  await userEvent.type(screen.getByLabelText('Email'), 'dev@example.com')
  await userEvent.type(screen.getByLabelText('Password'), 'secret123')
  await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /log in/i }))

  expect(await screen.findByText('Welcome back!')).toBeInTheDocument()
})$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
